description:
I recorded this while driving some back roads, following Buffalo Creek from its easternmost headwaters to its confluence with the the Ohio River at Wellsburg, as an outing for my 99 year old mother. She can still hear many birdsongs, and is always asking what birds we are hearing, 

The Cerulean Warbler is one I've never knowingly seen or heard before. It is uncommon around home, but there is some great habitat along parts of Buffalo Creek. We were driving slowly, listening to and recording as we went (in case of something unusual) lots of Warbler song east of Bethany, WV. While not the highest quality recording obviously, the bird was pretty close, and the song is very distinctive. I have a library of reference recordings on vinyl and CD, which I've put on my phone, and we now use the amazing Merlin smart phone program to help learn more birdsongs. 

This outing suggested a few good spots to spend more time with a good microphone and long camera lens some time soon.

description: Among others
Lifer!!

This area is a favorite of mine for its extensive contiguous deep woodland, protected as public land. Pennsylvania State Game lands No. 232 consists of 5,183 acres, broken up a bit by farms, but with some relatively remote and wild wooded stream valleys and ravines. This is one of the best places I know for finding unusual Warblers around here. 

This Cerulean Warbler was close, but invisible to me, likely high in the upper forest canopy. I was content to listen and record his song, and did not try to "pish" it down within view. I have never actually seen a Cerulean Warbler, but this one sang repeatedly, clearly, and unmistakably. 

A birding friend of mine saw Cerulean Warblers over at Bear Rock Lakes in WV on May 10th, and told me that they are the fastest declining Warbler in North America. I am so pleased we still have so much suitable habitat left here in Washington County to (help) support these amazing creatures. It is mind boggling to me that some of these birds spend their (or rather *our*) Winters down by the Andes in South America. 

I recorded the audio with a RØDE Stereo Videomic Pro microphone mounted on a Canon EOS Rebel T3i camera shooting video. The sonogram visually displays the sound frequencies, in this case between 1000 and 11,000 Hertz over three seconds time. Another bird quietly in the background is responsible for most of the highest frequencies; that is, those above 8 kilohertz or so. 

I took a photograph with my phone to record the location coordinates, and another at the same time that I wrote on with my finger to mark it as the location at which I recorded the Audio - all because my camera is incapable of marking the photos' and videos' locations in the metadata. Some extra steps required, but worth it to me for documenting such an exciting species.
